Lady Macbeth’s sleepwalking is presented as a punishment for her
actions. Her doctor implies that she has brought her “unnatural troubles”
(her sleepwalking) on herself by committing “Unnatural deeds” (evil acts).
Shakespeare repeatedly uses imagery of blood to symbolise guilt. For example, Lady Macbeth’s
attempts to wash imaginary blood off her hands when she sleepwalks expose her guilty conscience.
